  "riddle": "Here is the riddle with the requested changes:\n\n1. Seek the Wikipedia page of the notable figure known for her career as a professional wrestler and count the language links shown at the very top of that article; when done, use Wikipedia's search to find the well‑known Japanese women's pro‑wrestling promotion often shortened to a glittery, one‑word nickname.\n\n2. There exists a page for that all‑female promotion; note the date when it was founded as listed on the page, and then follow the link on its roster to the villainous stable whose name evokes an Edo‑period underworld.\n\n3. What date is given as the debut for that heel stable in its profile box?\n\n4. If you open the profile of the individual listed among that stable's notable members, record the date of her professional wrestling debut.\n\n5. The event article titled with a \"Dream Queendom\" banner holds a specific event date; read that page to find when the show occurred.\n\n6. In England there is a pottery town whose station serves the area — discover how many metres above sea level the ground sits in that town and write that elevation down.\n\n7. The number now needs a mirror for the next turn: reverse the digits of the elevation you just recorded to produce a new numeric value.\n\n8. (At the great junction town famed for its railworks) find how many platforms the main station there currently has.\n\n9. Now take that platform count and add together its individual digits to get the following number you will need.\n\n10. How many kilometres would you drive between Yorkshire's steel city and Japan's capital, if a driving route existed; find the driving distance between those two cities.\n\n11. If you inspect the rail stop serving the major airport near Manchester, note how many platforms that station has.\n\n12. The prime you seek is the next prime number after the platform count you just found at the airport station; identify that prime.\n\n13. In the ferry town on Anglesey, imagine a car journey to the junction town mentioned earlier — how many minutes would that drive take according to typical directions?\n\n14. Count the number of churches returned by a search for \"churches near Boston\" and record that count.\n\n15. Convert that church count to binary and then count how many 1‑bits appear in that binary representation; that tally is your next value.\n\n16. (Convert units now) Express four metres in feet and take the integer part of the result as your next number.\n\n17. Compute the final single‑digit answer as follows: take the absolute difference between clue 13 and clue 14, then take that result modulo 10 — the outcome is a single digit (0–9).",
